<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEARY MARINERS TAKE IT ALL OUT ON ANGELS; ANGELS: GRIFFEY HITS 37TH HOME RUN AS 
SEATTLE ROMPS TO A 10-2 VICTORY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Seattle Mariners arrived Tuesday afternoon at Anaheim Stadium in a rotten 
mood. They weren't supposed to be here in the first place until their roof 
started falling in at the Kingdome. Plans of playing in Tacoma were abandoned 
when the Angels protested. And if that weren't cruel enough, their off-day was 
spent traveling and playing in an exhibition game in Cooperstown, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
 They slowly walked into the visiting clubhouse at Anaheim Stadium, wondering 
how life can possibly get worse, and immediately were taken aback by a foul 
odor. The sewer had backed up and was seeping on the clubhouse floor. 
</P>
<P>
 "Beautiful," Mariner right fielder Jay Buhner said, "simply bleeping 
beautiful." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Ken Griffey Jr.: "I think we should bag this and go for a neutral site. 
Let's go to Peoria (Ariz.). They banged us. Let's bang them." 
</P>
<P>
 The Mariners cursed, angrily dressed, stepped onto the field, and unleashed 
their vented frustration upon the Angels, winning, 10-2, in front of 11,478 
fans -- the smallest Anaheim Stadium crowd since 1978. 
</P>
<P>
 "We stunk, we played like a bunch of triple-A players," Angel Manager Marcel 
Lachemann angrily said. "It was the worst exhibition of baseball we have put on 
all year, and it will not happen again. 
</P>
<P>
 "I take full responsibility. If I can't get them to play any better than that 
. . . I'm embarrassed, and if they're not embarrassed, it's a sad state of 
affairs." 
</P>
<P>
 Lachemann was particularly upset with starter Phil Leftwich, who was slow 
picking up a Felix Fermin grounder in the fifth inning, and threw the ball 
away. 
</P>
<P>
 "That was not acceptable," Lachemann said. "The only way he should throw the 
ball away is if he has a broken leg." 
</P>
<P>
 The game was played amid the sounds of heavy construction as the new 
scoreboard was being erected in the upper deck. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've seen just about everything this year," Buhner said. "You ever hear that 
expression, 'You learn something new every day.' Well, every day we see 
something new." 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels' biggest concern about this series is that their fans might be a 
bit rambunctious. Most never have had the opportunity to have such close seats 
for a major league game. 
</P>
<P>
 Who would have imagined the most unruly folks in the place would be the Angels 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 There was Bo Jackson getting called out on a third strike in the fourth inning 
and ejected by plate umpire Al Clark. Jackson became livid. He screamed at 
Clark, and retreated to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
 Uh-oh, out came a bag full of balls, 17 of which rolled onto the field. Out 
came a box full of sunflower seeds, with perhaps 40 being strewn. Out went 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
 In the sixth inning, there was Chili Davis striking out, and shattering the 
bat over his right knee, stalking to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a hell of a night," Mariner Manager Lou Piniella said, "I've never 
seen Bo Jackson get that mad. And Chili Davis. . . . you got to be strong to do 
that." 
</P>
<P>
 The game included Ken Griffey Jr.'s 37th home run, helping to end the 
Mariners' seven-game losing streak. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mariners' fourth and fifth hitters in the order combined for two homers 
and five runs batted in, the Angels' duo combined for six strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
 "Obviously, we'd like to play in a different place, but I can't blame the 
Angels for not wanting to play in Tacoma," Buhner said. "I feel the same way. I 
don't want to play in no triple-A ballpark either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
