<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAKE FOREST TO FILE SUIT OVER EL TORO INITIATIVE; DEVELOPMENT: CITY COUNCIL 
MEMBERS SAY THE BALLOT MEASURE, WHICH SUPPORTS A COMMERCIAL AIRPORT AT THE 
MARINE FACILITY, IS INCONSISTENT WITH THE COUNTY GENERAL PLAN AND PROMOTES 
CHAOS AND LITIGATION. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA and LILY DIZON, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an unexpected move, the Lake Forest City Council announced Tuesday night 
that it will file a lawsuit seeking to remove an initiative from the November 
ballot that calls for a commercial airport at the El Toro Marine Corps Air 
Station. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members emerged from a closed session to announce that they had voted 
unanimously to file a lawsuit against sponsors of the initiative, the Committee 
for 21,000 New Jobs, saying the measure is inconsistent with the county General 
Plan. 
</P>
<P>
 Immediately after their surprise announcement, council members issued a press 
release to explain their decision but made no other public statements. 
</P>
<P>
 "These inconsistencies, if adopted, will promote chaos and litigation over 
matters such as building intensity standards, traffic capabilities and noise 
problems," Mayor Marcia Rudolph said in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council maintains that the initiative will change the General Plan to 
allow a commercial airport but will not address other issues such as 
transportation and noise. 
</P>
<P>
 The measure also will bypass state planning laws, city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is another example of special-interest attempts to sell their products 
by 'ballot box planning,' of a piecemeal nature to circumvent a California 
environmental quality act," Councilman Tim Link said in the press release. 
</P>
<P>
 Some proponents of the initiative expressed surprise at the council's action 
but did not express concern. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was an initiative signed by over a 100,000 Orange County voters, far in 
excess of the requirement" to place it on the ballot, said Garden Grove 
Councilman Mark Leyes, who supports the initiative. By saying they will file a 
lawsuit, Lake Forest council members "don't give voters enough credit," Leyes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Buck Johns, a developer who is a major financial backer of the initiative, 
said, "It will be interesting to see what's going to happen. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 "Lake Forest has been pretty aggressive in this, haven't they?" Johns said. 
"This is the first I've heard" of a lawsuit. "I wish them well." 
</P>
<P>
 Lake Forest's announcement surprised even its allies.  
</P>
<P>
 "I wasn't even aware of this until now," said Mission Viejo Mayor Susan 
Withrow, a member of the South County Working Group, a coalition of cities that 
was established to create alternative proposals to a commercial airport. The 
group includes Lake Forest. 
</P>
<P>
 Withrow said the coalition rejected filing a similar lawsuit two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
 "We weren't confident of what the results would be," she said. "We didn't want 
the public to perceive a lawsuit as an elite action that would squelch the 
public's right to vote." 
</P>
<P>
 But a single-party lawsuit by Lake Forest wouldn't be elitist, Withrow said. 
</P>
<P>
 Along with Irvine and the County Board of Supervisors, Lake Forest is a member 
of the El Toro Reuse Planning Authority board of directors, set up to determine 
how the El Toro base should be used after its closure by 1999. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilwoman Ann Van Haun, Lake Forest's representative on the Planning 
Authority board, said the initiative would usurp the group's authority. 
</P>
<P>
 The authority, "established by the county of Orange and the cities of Irvine 
and Lake Forest, and recognized by the surrounding communities and the federal 
government as the local planning agency, would be completely short-circuited by 
a mandatory airport authority," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Lake Forest officials acknowledged that obtaining a court order to remove the 
initiative might be difficult. 
</P>
<P>
 "The city of Lake Forest has a duty to challenge the legality of the 
initiative," Councilman Richard T. Dixon said in the written statement. "If we 
do not take action now, people will wonder. If we do act now, we may succeed in 
knocking it off the ballot." 
</P>
<P>
 The initiative qualified in the June election primary with 118,000 signatures. 
Supporters backing the measure include numerous business and political leaders 
in the county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
